# VR performance — Quest 3

Quest 3 has a Snapdragon XR2 Gen 2 mobile SoC. **It is not a desktop GPU.** Treat every frame as a budget. Performance regressions are far more visible in VR than in 2D — sub-90 FPS or frame-time spikes cause user-perceived nausea.

## Targets

- **Refresh rate**: 90 Hz default (11.1 ms / frame). MVP target is 90 Hz, not 72.
- **CPU budget**: ~7 ms per frame.
- **GPU budget**: ~7 ms per frame.
- **Draw calls**: < 200 / eye (Quest 3 is generous compared to Quest 2 but stay below this).
- **Triangles**: < 750 k visible per frame (rough order of magnitude).
- **Texture memory**: < 1.5 GB resident.

Measure with **OVR Metrics Tool** on device — not Unity Profiler over Link (Mac can't anyway).

## Renderer

- URP only. No Built-in. No HDRP (HDRP is not viable on Quest 3 mobile GPU).
- Vulkan only. No OpenGLES.
- **Single Pass Instanced** or **Multiview** rendering — never Multi-pass.
- Use the **Universal Render Pipeline / Mobile / Lit** shader or the URP / Simple Lit family. Avoid HDRP shaders, Standard, or shaders with full PBR + complex BRDF.

## Lighting

- **Bake static lights.** No realtime shadows except one directional shadow casting only on dynamic objects.
- Reflection probes baked. No realtime reflection probes.
- LightProbeGroup for dynamic objects in baked scenes.

## Geometry

- LODs on anything > 5 k tris.
- GPU instancing on repeated props.
- Static batching on truly static meshes.
- Dynamic batching off for VR (rarely a win, costs CPU).

## Post-processing — minimal

Disable by default:

- ❌ Screen Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO)
- ❌ Bloom (or use the cheap variant only)
- ❌ Depth of Field
- ❌ Motion Blur
- ❌ Vignette
- ❌ Chromatic Aberration

Color grading via LUT is OK. Tonemapping ACES is OK.

## Anti-aliasing

- Use **MSAA 4x** at the RenderPipelineAsset level (Quest 3 supports it well, much cheaper than post-AA).
- No FXAA, no SMAA, no TAA (TAA + foveated rendering = visible artefacts).

## Foveated rendering

Enable **Eye-tracked Foveated Rendering** on Quest 3 (works without eye tracking too — falls back to fixed). Configure via `OVRManager` → Foveated Rendering Level: High during gameplay. Big GPU win essentially free of quality cost.

## Scripting

- Avoid `GameObject.Find`, `FindObjectOfType` at runtime — cache in Awake/Start.
- Avoid LINQ in hot paths (Update, FixedUpdate, OnRenderObject). LINQ allocates IEnumerators.
- No `string` concatenation in hot paths — use `StringBuilder` or pre-formatted strings.
- No `Camera.main` in Update — cache it.
- Allocations during recording / playback hot loops must be zero. Pre-allocate buffers for joint arrays.
- Use Job System + Burst for hand joint serialization timeline processing if it ever gets heavy.

## Audio

- Compress AudioClip to Vorbis quality 70-100, Load Type: Compressed In Memory for VO, Streaming for long clips.
- Mono for any spatialized source (mandatory for HRTF).
- Limit concurrent spatialized sources to ≤ 32 — Meta Spatializer cost is non-trivial.

## Build size

- Strip unused Meta SDK features via Project Setup Tool.
- Compress textures to ASTC 6x6 for diffuse, ASTC 4x4 for normal maps. Don't ship uncompressed.
- Code stripping: `Managed Stripping Level = Low` for MVP, `Medium` later (test thoroughly — strips reflection callbacks).
